#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:32
#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:202
msgid "User-to-Kernel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:34
msgid ""
"The user-to-kernel attack vector involves a malicious userspace program "
"attempting to leak kernel data into userspace by exploiting a CPU "
"vulnerability. The kernel data involved might be limited to certain kernel "
"memory, or include all memory in the system, depending on the vulnerability "
"exploited."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:39
msgid ""
"If no untrusted userspace applications are being run, such as with single-"
"user systems, consider disabling user-to-kernel mitigations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:42
msgid ""
"Note that the CPU vulnerabilities mitigated by Linux have generally not been "
"shown to be exploitable from browser-based sandboxes.  User-to-kernel "
"mitigations are therefore mostly relevant if unknown userspace applications "
"may be run by untrusted users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:47
msgid "*user-to-kernel mitigations are enabled by default*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:52
#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:202
msgid "User-to-User"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:54
msgid ""
"The user-to-user attack vector involves a malicious userspace program "
"attempting to influence the behavior of another unsuspecting userspace "
"program in order to exfiltrate data.  The vulnerability of a userspace "
"program is based on the program itself and the interfaces it provides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:59
msgid ""
"If no untrusted userspace applications are being run, consider disabling "
"user-to-user mitigations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:62
msgid ""
"Note that because the Linux kernel contains a mapping of all physical "
"memory, preventing a malicious userspace program from leaking data from "
"another userspace program requires mitigating user-to-kernel attacks as well "
"for complete protection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:67
msgid "*user-to-user mitigations are enabled by default*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:72
#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:202
msgid "Guest-to-Host"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:74
msgid ""
"The guest-to-host attack vector involves a malicious VM attempting to leak "
"hypervisor data into the VM.  The data involved may be limited, or may "
"potentially include all memory in the system, depending on the vulnerability "
"exploited."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:79
msgid ""
"If no untrusted VMs are being run, consider disabling guest-to-host "
"mitigations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:81
msgid ""
"*guest-to-host mitigations are enabled by default if KVM support is present*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:86
#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:202
msgid "Guest-to-Guest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:88
msgid ""
"The guest-to-guest attack vector involves a malicious VM attempting to "
"influence the behavior of another unsuspecting VM in order to exfiltrate "
"data.  The vulnerability of a VM is based on the code inside the VM itself "
"and the interfaces it provides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:93
msgid ""
"If no untrusted VMs, or only a single VM is being run, consider disabling "
"guest-to-guest mitigations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:96
msgid ""
"Similar to the user-to-user attack vector, preventing a malicious VM from "
"leaking data from another VM requires mitigating guest-to-host attacks as "
"well due to the Linux kernel phys map."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:100
msgid ""
"*guest-to-guest mitigations are enabled by default if KVM support is present*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:105
#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:202
msgid "Cross-Thread"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:107
msgid ""
"The cross-thread attack vector involves a malicious userspace program or "
"malicious VM either observing or attempting to influence the behavior of "
"code running on the SMT sibling thread in order to exfiltrate data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:111
msgid ""
"Many cross-thread attacks can only be mitigated if SMT is disabled, which "
"will result in reduced CPU core count and reduced performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:114
msgid ""
"If cross-thread mitigations are fully enabled ('auto,nosmt'), all "
"mitigations for cross-thread attacks will be enabled.  SMT may be disabled "
"depending on which vulnerabilities are present in the CPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:118
msgid ""
"If cross-thread mitigations are partially enabled ('auto'), mitigations for "
"cross-thread attacks will be enabled but SMT will not be disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:121
msgid ""
"If cross-thread mitigations are disabled, no mitigations for cross-thread "
"attacks will be enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:124
msgid ""
"Cross-thread mitigation may not be required if core-scheduling or similar "
"techniques are used to prevent untrusted workloads from running on SMT "
"siblings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/hw-vuln/attack_vector_controls.rst:127
msgid "*cross-thread mitigations default to partially enabled*"
msgstr ""

